                     <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18120916-218-off1177 t18120916-218-victim1757"></join>
                  </persName>
            .</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18120916-218-person1758">
                  JOSEPH 
                  MASKELL
               <interp inst="t18120916-218-person1758" type="surname" value="MASKELL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-218-person1758" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-218-person1758" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live in Barrow's-buildings, over Blackfriars-road. I am an <rs id="t18120916-218-viclabel1179" type="occupation">hackney coachman</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18120916-218-victim1757 t18120916-218-viclabel1179"></join>.</p>
               <p>Q. Did you lose a great coat - A. Yes, from my hackney coach. My coach was in <placeName id="t18120916-218-crimeloc1180">Bridge-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18120916-218-crimeloc1180" type="placeName" value="Bridge-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18120916-218-crimeloc1180" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18120916-218-off1177 t18120916-218-crimeloc1180"></join>, with my great coat in it. About half past two I missed it. I had seen it in the coach about ten minutes before. I was in the house at dinner when the coat was taken. There was an alarm, and I found the man in custody, and the great coat with them. I know the coat to be mine. It is worth five shillings.</p>
               <p>PETER LONG. I am an hackney coachman. I was on the stand in Bridge-street. Maskell's coach was next to mine. I was sitting on the box. A man gave me information. He told me to run up the street, I should catch the man with the coat. I ran up Union-street, towards Apothecaries-hall, and then to St. Andrew's-hill. I saw the prisoner with the coat under his arm. I laid hold of him, and brought him back, and delivered him up, with the coat, to Townshend, the officer.</p>
               <p>WILLIAM TOWNSHEND. I am the constable of Bridewell hospital. The coat and the prisoner was delivered to me. This is the coat.</p>
               <p>Prosecutor. It is my coat.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I saw the coat down by the horses heels. I picked it up. That goods man came and took me in Union-street.</p>
               <p>
                  <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="181209160108"></xptr> The prisoner called two witnesses, who gave him a good character.</p>
               <p>GUILTY, aged 36.</p>
               <p>
